How to Create a Kick-ass Portfolio Site that will WOW Your Next Employer
Tim Wong
Tim Wong

Follow
7 min read
¬∑
Jun 20, 2021
402

1

Press enter or click to view image in full size

Portfolio sites, the cornerstone to any great job application. They serve as a way to cultivate your personal branding and sell you and your skills out to the employer and the job market.

Today I‚Äôll walk you through how to create a kick-ass portfolio site that will impress and wow your next employer. So without further ado, let‚Äôs begin!

Step 1‚Äî Custom Domains
First and foremost, head over to Namecheap or GoDaddy and spend an ample amount of time shopping for your desired domain name, this is an important step as this domain name will serve as your personal brand‚Äôs name.

Your domain name should ideally be:

Containing your actual name
Memorable (easy to remember)
Meaningful
Easy To Read
If you have a fairly common name, your desired domain name will probably be taken by a doppelg√§nger somewhere across the globe. Fear not, try to use a different TLD such as .net | .gg |.dev | .cc | or even | .ai

Here are some good examples of selecting a name:

John Smith‚Äî https://thejohnsmith.dev

Harry Potter ‚Äî https://harrypotter.gg

Naruto Uzumaki ‚Äî https://narutouz.com

Step 2 ‚Äî Hosting Your Portfolio Site
Now that you have an address for the worldwide web, it‚Äôs time to select a hosting provider to build a house in that particular address.

Wix, WordPress, Squarespace are all awesome website builders & I personally love WordPress but when you‚Äôre building a portfolio site: you‚Äôre supposed to be showing off your skills in building an app/site. (does not apply ‚Äî if you‚Äôre looking for WordPress/Wix/Squarespace jobs)

Instead, use GitHub Pages. It‚Äôs entirely free and you get to show off your source code on your GitHub Profile. To start:

2.1 Create a new account

2.2 Create a new repository (repo) ‚Äî like this üëá

Press enter or click to view image in full size

We will need to link this repo to the custom domain later once we have it all ready and set up. More on that later.

Step 3 ‚Äî Bootstrap Templates
There are numerous CSS frameworks out there but Bootstrap remains the most popular CSS framework for a good reason. There are approximately 18 million sites on the web built using Bootstrap, so it‚Äôs a given that there will be more templates out there for Bootstrap versus other frameworks.

With that being said, finding a good Bootstrap template is crucial to building a beautiful and functional portfolio site. Here are some good sites to find from:

https://startbootstrap.com/themes
https://www.creative-tim.com/bootstrap-themes/free
https://themewagon.com/theme_tag/free/
https://themefisher.com/free-bootstrap-templates/
Most of these are free and the quality is definitely un-compromised. You may also choose premium ones as long as they‚Äôre within your budget.

You might also be wondering why we‚Äôre using a Bootstrap template and not writing it from scratch. Well, in fact, you can. But I believe there‚Äôs no need to reinvent the wheel because after all we‚Äôre not just downloading the template and changing it to our names.

Instead, we‚Äôll be using it as a foundation to build upon, therefore eliminating the need to recreate everything from scratch. üëçüèª

Step 4 ‚Äî Content Planning
Now that we have the barebones of the site from the portfolio templates, we need to plan how the content should be. Essentially your portfolio site should contain these information. In no particular order, but I found this arrangement to be most effective and provide the best user experience and reading flow.

4.1 Intro

This intro should be a short one-liner about yourself and describe a bit of your character/interests/personality. Here‚Äôs mine for reference: It has my name and job position, my favourite Apple devices on the left, and my hobbies on the right.

Press enter or click to view image in full size

You also shouldn‚Äôt give away too much on the first page because you want to capture the users' attention and encourage them to scroll down to learn more.

4.2 About Me

Here we can include a short write-up about ourselves, our past & our future goals. It may also be good to include your tech stack so that anyone reading can have a rough overview of what skills you have (and don‚Äôt have).

4.3 Projects

Pretty self explanatory but this is the most important part which will be viewed most often. This section will feature all the projects you‚Äôve done. You may even include projects at work that you‚Äôre genuinely proud of and of course your personal side projects.

Press enter or click to view image in full size

4.4 Blog (optional)

Having a blog is optional but highly recommended because it creates a personal branding. Using this, you can create a lasting effect in anyone‚Äôs minds with your personal interests, struggles and how you overcame them, and your goals in the future. Here I have some simple JavaScript code to pull a collection of posts from Medium.

4.5 Contact details

A great (portfolio) site wouldn‚Äôt be complete without an effective Call-To-Action (CTA) that creates ease for your potential employer to give you an email/call. A custom form that allows your users to send you an email, has proven to be highly effective. On top of that, you should also include LinkedIn/GitHub links for them to further interact with you.

Press enter or click to view image in full size

Step 5‚Äî Cleaning Up
5.1 .html extensions

If you‚Äôre using a Bootstrap template, chances are all href will be to another HTML page with a .html extension. This will make your links ugly like this.

Of course we don‚Äôt want that so we can remove the .html extension from all the href in every .html file & replace to using / instead. Here is an example üëá

Don‚Äôt worry about not being able to access the pages on localhost because GitHub Pages will handle all the routing for you, another reason why GitHub Pages is awesome.

5.2 Title & Description Tags
On top of every .html file make sure to include these two lines of code

<title>Tim Wong Portfolio Site | Software Engineer, Ex Flight Crew, Atomic Habits (JavaScript, Ruby, React, Python)</title>
<meta name="description" content="Tim Wong is a Software Engineer with a wide array of skills from programming, writing, design. Love to meet new people & learn all about startups and businesses.">
So that when you share the link of your portfolio site, it will include details as such, looks much better doesn‚Äôt it? üòâ

Press enter or click to view image in full size

Step 6‚Äî Deploying
Now we‚Äôre ready for the world to see your masterpiece. Go ahead and initialize your folder as a Git repository. Go back to the repo link and copy the command-line codes given by GitHub (refer to Step 2.2). The commands should look something like this:

git init
git add .
git commit -m "First commit"
git branch -M master
git remote add origin https://github.com/T31K/Portfolio-Site.git
git push -u origin master
If you do all the above successfully, your GitHub repo should look something like this. The last step is to tell GitHub to build the pages from the files you‚Äôve pushed.

Head over to Settings > Pages and

Select master or main branch to build your Pages from
Insert the custom domain that you‚Äôve set up from Step 1
Ensure you check Enforce HTTPS for secured browsing to your site

Step 7 ‚Äî Awe At Your Masterpiece
Congratulations, you‚Äôve successfully created your own portfolio site! Head over to the site and stare at it for as long as you want, appreciate the hard work you‚Äôve put in & give yourself a firm pat on the back.

Of course, this isn‚Äôt the end but it‚Äôs a very good start. This is just the beginning as you should regularly come back and update it, so that your content stays fresh and you keep your doors open to new opportunities and recruiters that are out hunting for suitable candidates.

As usual, take care and till next time.

~ Tim

